  "prompt": "Why is AC current more dangerous than DC current?",
  "response": "AC (Alternating Current) is generally considered more dangerous than DC (Direct Current) for several reasons:\n\n1. Frequency Effect\n- AC cycles 50-60 times per second\n- This frequency can cause muscle tetanus (continuous contraction)\n- Makes it harder to let go of a live wire\n- Increases likelihood of prolonged electrical shock\n\n2. Physiological Impact\n- AC can disrupt heart rhythm more easily\n- Can cause ventricular fibrillation more readily\n- Higher potential to stop heart function\n\n3. Skin Resistance\n- AC more effectively penetrates human skin\n- Lower resistance to AC current compared to DC\n- Greater potential for internal electrical damage\n\n4. Voltage Transformation\n- AC can be easily transformed to different voltage levels\n- More prevalent in power distribution systems\n- Higher voltage increases shock risk\n\n5. Sustained Current\n- AC's cyclical nature maintains continuous electrical path\n- DC tends to have more abrupt current flow\n\n6. Nerve Stimulation\n- AC more effectively stimulates nerve cells\n- Causes more severe muscular and neurological reactions\n\nWhile both currents are dangerous, AC's characteristics make it potentially more lethal, especially at higher voltages and frequencies.",
